The chef obviously knows how to make good food, but I was expecting more finesse. While the prices are high for a mid-scale restaurant, I think the establishment ultimately ends up serving big portions but compromising on quality. Maybe accessibility it important to the chef.  What I mean by this is-  the mussels we ordered were absolutely delicious- but the quality of the mussels itself  weren’t great. They were gritty with sand and very very little meat. It’s too much of a rich dish to have in volume so I think if the portion was smaller and they opted for meaty mussels, it would be even better.  I got the Corvina, which I noticed was served with creamy buttery sauce and rice. The thing that held the dish together was the sauce, which tasted like cream, salt and butter. Aside from the sauce, the fried fish was not seasoned and crispy; nor was the rice flavorful.  The heavy use of butter, salt and cream made me see the restaurant more as a French-Peruvian blend than something traditionally Peruvian- which is understandable because at a glance, you can tell the dishes are very experimental. Even the mussels had a very strong butter taste, so I imagine the chef REALLY loves his cream and butter. We ordered the causa too and that reminded me of a potato salad. The ceviche trio was excellent.  I think, as a consumer, what I missed the most was the sharp, fresh, and vibrancy  of Peruvian Cuisine. Despite Peruvian ingredients, I felt like the Peruvian roots of the menu were muted by other influences. The heavy use of mayo and cream made the food heavy, and lean more on the side of sashimi with spicy aioli as opposed to anything distinctly Peruvian.  Our waitress, who was sporting a golden pixie cut, was great but would be better as a host. She reminded me of a mother scorning her children for not eating the last bite. I’m sure it was innocent, but it felt uncomfortable when she’d ask us if we’d like the last bite of our dishes.  Overall- the food was very tasty. Not quite what I was expecting, but good. I think the decor and general exterior of the establishment didn’t align with the food being served. These dishes at heart felt like they could thrive in fine dining, but the decor and general ambiance was more Americana in Miami. This is a casual spot with big portions that is good for groups- I would recommend it for that.

Tonight is the first, and last, time we will eat here. My wife is Peruvian and we both looked forward to eating a good Peruvian meal. Unfortunately, half of our meal never came. We ordered our appetizers (ceviche and chicharron sliders) with our entrees (lamb shank and lomo saltado). The appetizers arrived - the ceviche mix was okay, but the fish had an aftertaste. The sliders were mostly sweet potato with very little pork. My lomo arrived and then we waited... and waited... and waited... for more than 45 minutes. No one came back to our table to ask us how the food was, or fill us in on the status of the lamb shank. When we finally got the attention of someone waiting on the table next to us we told her to cancel the lamb shank and bring our check. No one ever apologized for the hour we'd waited for an entree that never came, or offered any kind of explanation. What we ate was mediocre (half the lomo was warm, the other half lukewarm) and what we didn't is apparently still wandering around somewhere in Gowanus.
